information is adequately translated into the wide spectrum of cardiac responses, are still blurry. By combining the anatomical and structural information brought to light by recent imaging technologies and the functional evidence in cellular systems, we focus on the interface between neurons and cardiomyocytes, and advocate the existence of a speciﬁc ‘neuro-cardiac junction’, where sympathetic neurotransmission occurs in a ‘quasi-synaptic’ way. The properties of such junctional-type communication ﬁt well with those of the physiological responses elicited by the cardiac sympathetic nervous system, and explain its ability to tune heart function with precision, speciﬁcity and elevated temporal resolution.
