Sympathetic innervation of the heart: a network crowded with neuro-cardiac contacts
The whole mammalian heart is innervated by SNs, which enter the heart from the epicardium and extend their processes throughout the myocardial interstitium, running parallel to capillary vessels (Ieda et al. 2007; Kimura et al. 2012). Neuronal sympathetic processes display the characteristic pearl necklace morphology, with repeated enlargements (varicosities) where the neuroexocytosis apparatus localizes, releasing various neurotransmitters (mostly noradrenaline (NA), but also neuropeptide

